{/eq} ways to avoid three-of-a-kind. Since there are six possible values for the fifth die, there are {eq}6

{/eq} ways to make sure we have at least one pair. Thus, the number of ways the dice can land with at least one pair but no three-of-a-kind is {eq}720 \times 6 = 4320.

{/eq}
Hence, the probability the dice land with one or more pairs, but no three-of-a-kind is {eq}\dfrac{4320}{6^{5}} = \dfrac{80}{81}.

{/eq}

